latestIgtvVideos/0/caption:
In this Good Food Good Farming episode, young farmer Eliška Gálisová @dreamfarm.sk from Slovakia talks about how getting into farming is not just about the job, but it’s rather a change in the way we live, and how making it easier to access loans would greatly benefit young people in farming!

“Firstly, we need to change our approach and relationship to soil itself. 

Secondly, a farmer should have easier access to loans or grants in order to get their farm started. 

Lastly, it would be of great help if the State took part in facilitating distribution and selling channels for farmed products.” 

🇪🇺 These are Eliška’s requests to ensure better food and farming in Europe! 👉 What are yours?

#SlowFood #GoodCleanFair #SlowFoodEurope #GoodFoodGoodFarming @slowfood_pressburg

🐌 Today on our #SlowBeans journey, in collaboration with @meatlessmonday, we present the Acerra “Dente di Morto” bean, traditionally grown on the slopes of Mount Vesuvius in Campania!

🌱 Producers of this bean recognize the legume as an essential element of their culture, but also as a symbol of sustainable agriculture. That's why they’ve joined Slow Beans, a Slow Food network of legume producers, driven by strong relationships over shared values.

Watch as Luigi Russo, a chef from nearby Somma Vesuviana, prepares one of the most iconic dishes of the Campania region and mayor Raffaele Lettieri announcing these beans to be included in the menus of school cafeterias in Acerra!

👉 Want to find out more? Add your city to the map of municipalities committed to promoting a sustainable and climate-friendly diet!

#LetItBean #SlowBeans #SlowFood #MeatlessMonday

latestIgtvVideos/2/caption:
🐌 Today, our #SlowBeans journey brings us to the Umbrian Apennines, in Civita di Cascia, where the summers are hot and the winters very cold. It is here that roveja, a wild pea, which has almost disappeared today and has been recovered thanks to the discovery of a handful of seeds!

The harvesting of the roveja can be very tedious: it is mowed by hand, spending hours bent down to the ground. It’s valuable properties though, such as high iron content and versatility in the kitchen, makes it all worth it. Chef Valentina Dugo shares a recipe for roveja in a summer dish - a tabbouleh with celery, lemon and aromatic herbs!

Mario De Carolis, mayor of Cascia, has gladly joined the #LetItBean campaign, committing himself to support local producers with initiatives for the promotion of the legume, involving also schools and together with @MeatlessMonday starting a path towards a healthy and climate friendly diet!

👉 Want to find out more? Add your city to the map of municipalities committed to promoting a sustainable and climate-friendly diet!

latestIgtvVideos/3/caption:
🐌 When the pandemic hit Albania, @mrizi_i_zanave, a restaurant in the hills of Fishtë based on short supply chains, local products and seasonality, had to close. Altin Prenga, who founded the restaurant together with his brother Anton, was faced with a dilemma common to many restaurateurs during the lockdown period: what to do with their staff? 

More than 70 employees, mostly working in the kitchen and dining room suddenly found themselves out of a job. True to its credo of providing dignity through work, Altin decided to continue paying their salaries as long as they were making themselves useful to the community. But it didn’t end there for Altin. At the same time he developed a supply system for nearby cities, including the capital Tirana, ensuring that good food could reach the tables of citizens confined to their homes.

“At @mrizi_i_zanave we were leveraging our brand, guaranteeing quality and supporting farmers in an alternative way.” 

👉 FULL STORY through our LINK IN BIO

Financed by @europeanculturalfoundation with the contribution of @fondazionecrc, Slow Food Heroes tells the stories of those who stepped up to the crisis, in their own words. Some stories show the creativity of individuals, other the relentless work they carried out, each of them inspiring us to be heroes, in our own way, in our own communities.

🐌 Our journey to discover the legumes of the Slow Food Presidia along with Meatless Monday continues this week, as we stop in Tuscany!

Capannori is a small town in the province of Lucca, home to the #SlowBeans network and a wide variety of local legumes, which are fundamental ingredients of the area's gastronomy. 

The undisputed king? The Lucca red bean, a Slow Food Presidium, which chef Elena Pardini cooks in the traditional Tuscan Frantoiana soup together with braised cabbage!

The mayor of Capannori, Luca Menesini, acknowledges that farmers of this bean are also acting custodians and so, together with other municipalities, will host the next edition of Slow Beans, an event that brings together Italian farmers who cultivate traditional beans. 

👉 Join the #SlowBeans network and Meatless Monday and add at your city to the map of municipalities committed to promoting a delicious, climate-friendly diet!

Learn more through our LINK IN BIO!

#LetItBean #SlowBeans #SlowFood #MeatlessMonday #GoodCleanFair

latestIgtvVideos/5/caption:
🐌 Can #Legumes really change the world? Well, we and our friends at @meatlessmonday think they can! Legumes are so valuable for the environment and for our health, and that's why we want their production and consumption to become ever more widespread. Just think of what would happen if more mayors and more cities around the world would start to adopt these practices! 

This is the goal of #LetItBean, the campaign launched during Terra Madre 2020, which will be going on for the next six weeks on a journey across the country to discover the municipalities that, through different initiatives, have chosen to support local legume producers and promote a climate-friendly diet! 

👉 Stay tuned for all the next campaign updates and (why not?) take part in the campaign by contacting your municipality and asking them to join!

Together, we can make it hap-bean! 😉

More info through LINK IN BIO

#LetItBean #SlowBeans #SlowFood #MeatlessMonday #GoodCleanFair
latestIgtvVideos/6/caption:
🐌 In this last day of the Food for Change 2021 campaign with @relaischateaux, Julien Dumas (@dumasjulien), the new chef of the @saintjamesparis, tells us about a cheese that he enjoys thanks to his cheesemonger and "Meilleur Ouvrier de France" friend Bernard (@bernardmureravaud). While the tradition for this cheese dates back to the 18th century, Persillé de Tignes is no longer made, except for one producer: the Marmottan family farm. 

But why has this cheese gone out of fashion? The Tignes dam, built in the 1950s, submerged the old village and forced the population to leave. Instead, a burgeoning mountain tourist trade appeared and replaced demanding age-old practices, such as the Persillé de Tignes. Today, this excellent product represents the commitment required from communities everywhere to protect culinary heritage. 

🙌 Thank you to everyone who has made this year’s campaign a reality. Find the ALL STORIES and nominated #ArkOfTaste products through our LINK IN BIO!

#relaischateaux #slowfood #foodforchange #tastebiodiversity #onechefoneingredient #consciousconsumption @slowfoodenfrance
latestIgtvVideos/7/caption:
Jaisal Singh (@jaisalsujansingh) – Vice President of @relaischateaux and founder of SUJÁN (@thesujanlife) – explains to us that his love for Rajasthan is a family legacy. His parents explored the region in the 1970s, and they truly fell in love with the little-known paradise that is Ranthambore National Park. They have been committed to protecting tigers and other wildlife ever since. This includes the kumatiya tree, which has a great deal of appeal. 

In addition to being a part of the territory’s traditional agroforestry system and a source of complementary revenue with its gum arabic, it also offers a gratifying gourmet treat: its seeds. But the development of industrial agriculture in the region, as elsewhere in the world, poses a threat to the kumatiya, which cannot hold its own when compared to other species that produce more gum arabic. 

We need to remember the wise approach of respecting soil and discontinuing focus on single high-yield crops. As the proverb goes, “Don’t put all your eggs in one basket.

Find all #FoodFodChange 2021 stories through the LINK IN BIO!

#relaischateaux #slowfood #foodforchange #tastebiodiversity #onechefoneingredient #consciousconsumption @slowfoodindiaofficial
latestIgtvVideos/8/caption:
🐌 Today’s story comes from Chef Kyle Connaughton (@kyleconnaughton) and farmer Katina Connaughton (@lumberjackieo) of @singlethreadfarms in California, as they give us a tour of their farm's Gravenstein apple trees. 

“Biodiversity is like an insurance policy against climate change, a treasure that supports us as we face these new situations.”, shares Katina.

The #GravensteinApple is a symbol of the Sonoma County community. Brought here by Russian trappers in the early 19th century, it has provided food and drink for the locals for many years. Nevertheless, in the last decades, its cultivated area has been reduced to one-tenth of its former expanse. 

“Our culinary heritage is also very important because it reminds us of where we come from. That is why we chose the Gravenstein apple of Sebastopol, which is part of the identity of Sonoma County.” 

Find the FULL STORY through the @relaischateaux LINK IN BIO!

#relaischateaux #slowfood #foodforchange #tastebiodiversity #onechefoneingredient #consciousconsumption @slowfoodusa  @slowfoodsf
latestIgtvVideos/9/caption:
Today’s #FoodForChange story features Valdarno Black Chicken, nominated to the Ark of Taste by Chef Gaetano Trovato from @arnolforistorante in Italy, part of the @relaischateaux family.

Through this beautifully crafted short, Gaetano introduces us to his cuisine and to Laura Pieri, a poultry farmer who supplies his restaurant with Valdarno black chicken.

The Valdarno black chicken is a very rustic breed unsuitable for intensive farming. In fact, that is one of the reasons that it disappeared from the Tuscan countryside during the 20th century.

In today’s world of speed and simplification, Gaetano and Laura have chosen to complicate their lives and take their time and to pass along the identity of this territory to future generations: its extensiveness, its uniqueness, and its authentic clout. Biodiversity also means cultural diversity: it makes the world richer and more beautiful.

Extract taken from article by Eugenio Mailler, Instants Magazine

👉 Discover the full #FoodForChange campaign, through the LINK IN BIO!

🐌 Want to take part in a new era that sees coffee as a means to conserving nature and #biodiversity, social inclusiveness, transparency and #traceability?

This October 1st, we’ll be officially launching the #SlowFoodCoffeeCoalition, a new network we care deeply about, and that we have set up together with @lavazzaofficial!

The Slow Food Coffee Coalition is an #open network that aims to bring together farmers, traders, roasters, baristas, cooks, consumers, companies and institutions who want to commit to acting collaboratively towards:

☕️ Creating new connections and improving relationships in the coffee supply chain
☕️ Increasing the visibility of those who grow it
☕️ Promoting coffee identity and culture
☕️ Creating more awarenessin the enjoyment of coffee

While 2020 and 2021 were years of resilience, 2022 is a year of regeneration, of radical renewal and real agroecological transitions that can and must begin with food: by improving our agricultural practices, our systems of production and distribution, our diets and consumption and habits, from the largest cities to the smallest villages.

We return to Turin and Piedmont with all its colors, aromas and voices. However, beyond the physical event, #TerraMadre2022 will be a hybrid physical and digital event with calendar of activities organized by the Slow Food network around the world, for those who cannot travel to Turin.

The regeneration we’re talking about isn’t just the joy of meeting in person again. It’s an act of responsibility, of love and care for our home, the Earth, or Terra Madre. It's #RegenerAction.
latestPosts/1/caption:
🍅 When you go to the supermarket, you probably take a few seconds to choose each product you buy. Read labels here and there to know where it comes from or what's in them? 
It makes sense to be curious about what you'll be putting on your plate and your family's. 
Here's the thing, right now in the EU, all GMOs (old and new) must be risk-assessed, clearly labeled, and traceable throughout the whole food chain. Why? Because all consumers, farmers, and food producers have the right to know what is in their food and feed. 
Yet, this positive status quo is being challenged by the agri-food industry, which wants the European Union to deregulate new GMOs. 
They want to produce and sell them more easily, meaning that all the safety nets we mentioned would be removed. 
🙀 Who would be able to tell which foods are GMO-free? 
If you are as outraged as we are, please sign our petition and tell your decision-makers #IChooseGMOFree
👉 Link in Bio to sign the petition! ✏️

#SlowFood #GoodCleanFair

☕ This year, the first batch of Good, Clean and Fair coffee from Mexico will be available at Terra Madre 2022! They have joined the Coffee Coalition, which finds its grounds in a simple logic of a harmonious relationship with nature and between people.
👉 The producers of the coffee belong to the original Nahua people and are members of the Community Forest, Fog, and Coffee Xalapa, located in the State of Veracruz. This small achievement opens a path that we hope many communities in Mexico will follow to access international markets and strengthen local trade and consumption networks within the country.
👀 If you want to know more, visit the site of the Slow Food Coffee Coalition: coffeecoalition.slowfood.com

latestPosts/4/caption:
👂 Did you hear? Big agri-food companies and their lobbyists are pushing the European Union to deregulate new GMOs (a new generation of genetically modified organisms). At the moment, new GMOs are subject to EU GMO rules which state that they must be risk-assessed, clearly labeled and traceable throughout the whole food chain.

If new GMOs are excluded from these rules, farmers, food producers, retailers and consumers would no longer be able to choose what is in their food and feed, because they would no longer know what it contains. 

⚠️The European Commission is getting ready to decide on whether and how to deregulate these new GMOs, yet most Europeans haven’t even heard about them. 

👉Time for a quick recap !

✏️Also, don’t forget to sign the #IChooseGMOPetition to keep #newGMOs strictly regulated, and to spread the word about it!
Use the LINK IN BIO to sign!

#SlowFood #GoodCleanFair

🐝 How to choose honey if we are not experts? Don't worry. We have your back!
We asked Alessandra Giovannini from the Honey Ambassadors Association and professor of honey sensory analysis.

"You always have to choose labeled jars of honey. The most important information is the geographical origin. We have the right to know where the food we eat comes from and to have a choice."

🍯I recommend preferring an organic product or one that adds other qualities. Social cooperatives, companies that operate in penal institutions or with immigrant communities are an example.

🐌 Go to your local market, and ask questions. It is even better if we find the producer who tells us all the vicissitudes of the product (directly or through a website). 

#Guidetohoney #GoodCleanFair #SlowFood #Honey #Beekeeping #Beefriendly
latestPosts/7/caption:
🇺🇦 Updates from #Ukraine 

When her husband got drafted into the army at the beginning of the war, Olena Tovsta found herself alone managing the entire family farm “Dobro Craft”, in the region of Poltava. Through the “Together for the Slow Food Communities in Ukraine” campaign, Olena received the resources that allowed her family to keep the farm alive.

“The situation on the ground has not changed for the better, even where there is no military action: the entire population of Ukraine lives under the constant threat of missile attacks. We are tired and scared, but we are trying to resist.”

👉 Thanks to everyone for your generous support. If you haven’t already, please consider donating to directly support the people and communities on the ground that need it most -> LINK IN BIO

🌊 For a very long time, humanity thought the resources from the ocean were infinite, and nothing could harm it. 
🐠But we were wrong, our way of living, producing, and eating has caused oceans to come to a critical state. Now, they face acidification, deoxygenation, pollution, overfishing, and plankton decline. 
🛶 It is time to do our part! How?
* Research, learn and understand the problems.
* Leave nothing behind. 
* No plastic!
* Support sustainable fisheries.
* Discover Slow Fish! 
🐋 Do you have more advices to care for the ocean? Tell us!
#slowfish #slowfood #worldoceansday #protectouroceans🌎🐬🌊 #sustainableseafood

🐌 Imagine how much we could do if people worked together! Meet Andrés Jara, another one of our #SlowFoodHeroes who shared with us the story of how from a crisis, opportunities are born.

🍚 His project: Roots, Rice & Beans, started in the middle of the pandemic in 2020 when Andrés realized his neighboring farmers could not sell their products since all the restaurants were closed due to the lockdown, and that is where creativity and the will to make a change stepped in.

🥬 After a couple of months of the project, more than five tons of agricultural surplus were saved instead of becoming food waste.

👉 Find out more about this incredible story through our LINK IN BIO!

latestPosts/11/caption:
🎙️ The SFYN podcast series on EU food policies is back with a new name: Slow Food Goes Brussels! In this episode, we tell you the story of the many paradoxes of animal welfare in Europe with our guests: 
	• Jacopo Goracci, farmer of local ancient breeds of cows and pigs in rural Tuscany (Italy) and coordinator of a Slow Food Presidium
	• Andrea Gavinelli, who is in charge of the animal welfare unit at the EU Commission
	• Olga Kikou, European Affairs Manager at the organization Compassion in World Farming @ciwf
📣 Find the link in our bio!
🐄 The protection of animal welfare on farms has gained momentum in recent years in Europe, and more and more EU citizens are calling for the end of their cruel exploitation. 
🐂 Yet, it is said that the European Union has the most advanced legislation regarding animal welfare standards. So why such a gap between European law and farming practices? This and more questions/answers on this episode!
🎧 Tune in to be part of the conversation!
@slowfoodyouthnetwork @europeancommission
#sfyn #sfynpodcast #slowfood #animalwelfare #slowfoodeurope

Newspread - Artigiani punici in Sardegna
Nell’antica città di Tharros, in Sardegna, sta venendo alla luce un quartiere artigianale punico, con il rinvenimento di alcune fornaci per la produzione di ceramica vascolare risalenti a un periodo compreso tra il VI e il IV secolo a.C.
 
Si tratta di una scoperta molto importante, dal momento che sono rari i casi noti di veri e propri quartieri produttivi nel Mediterraneo centrale, a oggi concentrati per lo più in Sicilia e Nord Africa.

La professoressa Anna Chiara Fariselli del Dipartimento di Beni Culturali ci parla delle indagini di superficie e geofisiche condotte in collaborazione con il Dipartimento di Storia Culture e Civiltà.

#Newspread è la rubrica di videonotizie in collaborazione tra Unibo Magazine e @mmpwebtv .

#Unibo #ricerca #archeologia #Tharros @uniboper
latestIgtvVideos/1/caption:
Newspread - Un dente da latte di 13.000 anni fa, oggi racconta i movimenti dei cacciatori-raccoglitori nel Nord Italia.

In uno dei ripari delle Grotte di Pradis, nelle Prealpi Friulane, circa 13.000 anni fa un bambino di 11 o 12 anni ha perso un dente da latte. Dal reperto un’indagine multidisciplinare, guidata da studiosi Unibo e pubblicata su Scientific Reports del gruppo Nature, ha potuto ricostruire le strategie di mobilità stagionale dei gruppi umani dell’area nel tardo Paleolitico superiore. 

Allo studio, per l’Università di Bologna, hanno partecipato Federico Lugli, Rita Sorrentino, Antonino Vazzana, Eugenio Bortolini, Gregorio Oxilia, Sara Silvestrini, Luca Bondioli, Matteo Romandini e Stefano Benazzi del Dipartimento di Beni Culturali, insieme a Sahra Talamo del Dipartimento di Chimica “Giacomo Ciamician”.

#Newspread è la rubrica di videonotizie in collaborazione tra Unibo Magazine e @mmpwebtv.

#Unibo #ricerca @uniboper
latestIgtvVideos/2/caption:
Newspread - Aldrovandi 500. Ricorre quest’anno il cinquecentenario della nascita di Ulisse Aldrovandi (Bologna 11 settembre 1522 - 4 maggio 1605), fondatore di uno dei primi Orti botanici in Italia e creatore di uno dei primi musei naturalistici in Europa. Nei prossimi mesi si svolgeranno convegni, conferenze, spettacoli, mostre, visite guidate e altri eventi, organizzati da Unibo in onore di uno dei suoi figli più illustri.

Dal prof. Roberto Balzani, Presidente del Sistema Museale di Ateneo, uno sguardo su Ulisse Aldrovandi e sui motivi per cui la sua figura è così importante per l’Alma Mater.

Il sito con tutte le iniziative per il cinquecentenario aldrovandiano > https://site.unibo.it/aldrovandi500/it

#Newspread è la rubrica di videonotizie in collaborazione tra Unibo Magazine e @mmpwebtv 

#Unibo #Aldrovandi500 @museiunibo @uniboper

latestIgtvVideos/3/caption:
Newspread - L’intelligenza artificiale “a misura di paziente”. Cuore del progetto europeo MAIA è la realizzazione di tecnologie assistive affidabili, multifunzionali, adattabili e interattive, che potranno essere guidate direttamente dal cervello dei pazienti. Un’intelligenza artificiale che possa controllare neuroprotesi e altri dispositivi tecnologici applicati a braccia robotiche, sedie elettroniche ed esoscheletri. L’obiettivo è quello di fornire a chi abbia abilità motorie ridotte degli strumenti tecnologici che permettano una vita indipendente.

Finanziato dalla Commissione europea nell’ambito del programma Horizon 2020, il progetto è coordinato dall’Università di Bologna in capo al Dipartimento di Scienze Biomediche e Neuromotorie e nell'ambito di un consorzio multidisciplinare. 

L’approfondimento della professoressa Annalisa Bosco.

#Newspread è la rubrica di videonotizie in collaborazione tra Unibo Magazine e @mmpwebtv.

#Unibo #ricerca #ArtificialIntelligence #AI #IntelligenzaArtificiale @uniboper

Newspread - Un nuovo target terapeutico per il tumore del colon-retto. Uno studio ha mostrato per la prima volta il ruolo nello sviluppo del tumore del colon-retto di un recettore di membrana chiamato AKL, una proteina già nota per avere un ruolo oncogenico nel tumore al polmone e per la quale sono già disponibili farmaci inibitori.

L’approfondimento della professoressa Mattia Lauriola del Dipartimento di Medicina Specialistica Diagnostica e Sperimentale - DIMES, che ha coordinato lo studio.

#Newspread è la rubrica di videonotizie in collaborazione tra Unibo Magazine e @mmpwebtv.

#Unibo #ricerca @uniboper
latestIgtvVideos/6/caption:
Newspread - Ci sono anche virus buoni: una nuova terapia mirata contro il cancro si basa sull’azione di un fago, un virus che infetta i batteri, geneticamente modificato. Il fago è un virus innocuo per gli esseri umani, ingegnerizzato geneticamente e modificato chimicamente per eliminare in modo selettivo solo le cellule tumorali. Il trattamento, mirato e non invasivo, viene attivato dalla luce.
 
Lo studio, che ha conquistato la copertina della rivista Nanoscale, è stato realizzato da un gruppo di ricerca dell’Università di Bologna nell’ambito del progetto NanoPhage, sostenuto da Fondazione AIRC per la ricerca sul cancro.

#Newspread è la rubrica di videonotizie in collaborazione tra Unibo Magazine e @mmpwebtv
 
#Unibo #ricerca @airc.it @uniboper
latestIgtvVideos/7/caption:
Newspread - I buchi neri hanno i capelli?

Due nuovi articoli scientifici mostrano che i buchi neri hanno un campo gravitazionale che, a livello quantistico, codifica le informazioni su come si sono formati: una scoperta che aiuta a risolvere il paradosso dell'informazione del buco nero formulato da Stephen Hawking. La novità presentata modifica in modo significativo le conoscenze sui buchi neri, e risolve un problema su cui gli scienziati di tutto il mondo si sono interrogati per quasi mezzo secolo.

L’approfondimento del professor Roberto Casadio del Dipartimento di Fisica e Astronomia "Augusto Righi" dell'Università di Bologna e dell'INFN di Bologna.

Newspread è la rubrica di videonotizie in collaborazione tra Unibo Magazine e @mmpwebtv.

#Unibo #Newspread @uniboper

Newspread - Sensore per misurare gli anticorpi contro SARS-CoV-2

Un nuovo dispositivo, messo a punto da un gruppo di ricerca guidato da studiosi dell’Università di Bologna, consente la misurazione rapida, efficace, affidabile ed economica del livello di anticorpi neutralizzanti contro SARS-CoV-2 presenti nel sangue.

Il sensore consentirà di testare l’efficacia di nuovi vaccini anti COVID-19 e di rilevare gli anticorpi anche per altri virus.

Newspread è la rubrica di videonotizie in collaborazione tra Unibo Magazine e @mmpwebtv.

“Pier Paolo Pasolini. Folgorazioni figurative” è la nuova mostra per il centenario della nascita dell’artista, nato a Bologna il 5 marzo 1922. L'esposizione inaugura i nuovi spazi del Sottopasso di Piazza Re Enzo e segue la traccia che la città di Bologna ha lasciato nel percorso e nelle opere di Pasolini.

“Folgorazioni figurative” è a cura del prof. Marco Antonio Bazzocchi, Roberto Chiesi e Gian Luca Farinelli, promossa dalla Cineteca di Bologna, nell’ambito delle celebrazioni del Comune di Bologna e di quelle del Comitato nazionale per il Centenario della nascita di Pasolini, con il patrocinio dell'Universita di Bologna e il sostegno del Ministero della Cultura e della Regione Emilia-Romagna.

Newspread è la rubrica di videonotizie in collaborazione tra Unibo Magazine e @mmpwebtv.

La prima stima realizzata a livello globale indica come sulla Terra ci siano 9.000 specie di alberi ancora da scoprire: le specie arboree sarebbero circa 73.000, il 14% in più rispetto a quelle attualmente note.

Circa un terzo delle specie ancora sconosciute sarebbero rare, un dato che sottolinea la grande ricchezza degli ecosistemi e anche l’alta vulnerabilità ai cambiamenti prodotti dell’uomo. Lo studio è stato pubblicato sulla rivista PNAS. 

Newspread è la rubrica di videonotizie in collaborazione tra Unibo Magazine e @mmpwebtv.

latestPosts/10/caption:
Nelle persone con un elevato livello di intelligenza le diverse aree del cervello sono più connesse e comunicanti tra loro rispetto alla media, e sono particolarmente solide le connessioni a lungo raggio, quelle cioè tra aree cerebrali fisicamente lontane l’una dall’altra.

A confermarlo è uno studio pubblicato su Scientific Reports, rivista del gruppo Nature, frutto di una collaborazione internazionale tra Università di Bologna, Università di Oxford (Regno Unito) e Università di Aarhus (Danimarca). 

➡ LINK in BIO

Different areas of the brain are more connected and communicating with each other in people with a high level of intelligence than the average person. Long-range connections, i.e. those between brain areas that are physically distant from each other, are particularly strong. 

This is confirmed by a study published in Scientific Reports, a journal of the Nature group. The study is the result of an international collaboration between the University of Bologna, Oxford University (UK) and Aarhus University (Denmark). 

➡ LINK in BIO

#Unibo #ricerca @oxford_uni @aarhusuni #research #intelligenza #brain

"Nuovi percorsi dalla istruzione e formazione al lavoro: le innovazioni nell’alta formazione in Emilia-Romagna."

Il Bando è rivolto a:
- neolaureati (laurea triennale, laurea magistrale, master), laureandi (laurea triennale, laurea magistrale, master), dottorandi di ricerca, nell’ambito delle scienze naturali, ambientali, economiche e sociali;
- giovani ricercatori (dottori di ricerca, ricercatori disoccupati o con contratti atipici) che presentino un curriculum coerente alla richiesta della borsa di ricerca.

Per consultare il bando e per maggiori informazioni:
👉 http://www.centrostudileonardomelandri.it/

🧠 Open Your Mind 2022 🧠

Siamo lieti di annunciare l'evento Open Your Mind di quest'anno a tema Quantum Computing ⚛️

💻 In questo appuntamento scopriremo come le leggi della meccanica quantistica possono essere applicate per risolvere problemi troppo complessi per i computer classici. 

👥 Il professor Marco Chiani, esperto in teoria dell'informazione, ci illustrerà il paradigma del Quantum Computing fornendoci una panoramica generale e le sue proprietà e caratteristiche più rilevanti. Esploreremo inoltre i principali  spazi di applicazione e alcune previsioni sul futuro dei computer quantistici.

🍕L'evento sarà gratuito e verrà offerto un fantastico buffet al termine del seminario.

📆 Giovedì 21 Aprile, alle ore 17:00.
📍 Aula 2.12, Campus di Cesena.

🖥️ Sarà possibile seguire l'evento online, sulla piattaforma Microsoft Teams, seguendo il link in bio.

Stasera si fa la storia!

Stasera, 27 Maggio 2020, per la prima volta, l'azienda privata SpaceX manderà due americani nello spazio! Non solo: per la prima volta dal 2011, dalla dismissione dello Space Shuttle, un razzo americano porterà degli astronauti in orbita.
Il tutto avverrà su suolo americano; nel dettaglio, il lancio è previsto dalla storica piattaforma 39A di Cape Canaveral (Florida), la stessa da cui partivano le missioni Apollo e lo Space Shuttle.

latestIgtvVideos/8/caption:
Tra le tante risate che @giovannivernia ci ha regalato, nella diretta di Mercoledì, ci siamo soffermati su alcuni punti molto seri. Abbiamo parlato infatti di chi odia e di chi si lamenta.
Se ritenete troppo pessimistica la nostra visione consideriamola come provocazione e come incentivo a migliorare per davvero. Facciamo in modo che tutto questo cambi mettendo in ombra chi odia per sport.
Lo possiamo fare inoltrando più messaggi positivi alle persone che ci vogliono bene e cercando di aiutare di più chi ne ha bisogno.
Lo possiamo fare dando il giusto peso a ciò che veramente conta e a chi veramente conta.
Non è facile, in particolar modo nel periodo che stiamo vivendo, ma dovremmo essere anche molto devoti alle persone che ci strappano risate, come Giovanni Vernia.
Tutti i passaggi drammatici sono storicamente un passaggio, più o meno lento, ad un cambiamento. Aiutiamoci a farlo diventare miglioramento.
Cosa ne pensate?
#ingegneriadelsuicidio #ingegneria#università #giovannivernia
